[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Input and output operations on a computer can be extremely slow compared to the processing of data.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] An I/O device can incorporate mechanical devices that must physically move, such as a hard drive seeking a track to read or write; this is often orders of magnitude slower than the switching of electric current.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] For example, during a disk operation that takes ten milliseconds to perform, a processor that is clocked at one gigahertz could have performed ten million instruction-processing cycles.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] A simple approach to I/O would be to start the access and then wait for it to complete.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] But such an approach, called **synchronous I/O** or **blocking I/O**, would block the progress of a program while the communication is in progress, leaving system resources idle.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] When a program makes many I/O operations (such as a program mainly or largely dependent on user input), this means that the processor can spend almost all of its time idle waiting for I/O operations to complete.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Alternatively, it is possible to start the communication and then perform processing that does not require that the I/O be completed.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is called asynchronous input/output.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating system functions exist to implement asynchronous I/O at many levels.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] In fact, one of the main functions of all but the most rudimentary of operating systems is to perform at least some form of basic asynchronous I/O, though this may not be particularly apparent to the user or the programmer.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] In the simplest software solution, the hardware device status is polled at intervals to detect whether the device is ready for its next operation.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] (For example, the CP/M operating system was built this way.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Multitasking operating systems can exploit the functionality provided by hardware interrupts, whilst hiding the complexity of interrupt handling from the user.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Spooling was one of the first forms of multitasking designed to exploit asynchronous I/O.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Finally, multithreading and explicit asynchronous I/O APIs within user processes can exploit asynchronous I/O further, at the cost of extra software complexity.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Asynchronous I/O is used to improve energy efficiency, and in some cases throughput.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] However, it can have negative effects on latency and throughput in some cases.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] All forms of asynchronous I/O open applications up to potential resource conflicts and associated failure.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Careful programming (often using mutual exclusion, semaphores, etc.) is required to prevent this.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] When exposing asynchronous I/O to applications there are a few broad classes of implementation.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The form of the API provided to the application does not necessarily correspond with the mechanism actually provided by the operating system; emulations are possible.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Furthermore, more than one method may be used by a single application, depending on its needs and the desires of its programmer(s).
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating systems provide more than one of these mechanisms, it is possible that some may provide all of them.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] In a multitasking operating system, processing can be distributed across different processes, which run independently, have their own memory, and process their own I/O flows; these flows are typically connected in pipelines.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Processes are fairly expensive to create and maintain, so this solution only works well if the set of processes is small and relatively stable.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] It also assumes that the individual processes can operate independently, apart from processing each other's I/O; if they need to communicate in other ways, coordinating them can become difficult.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] An extension of this approach is dataflow programming, which allows more complicated networks than just the chains that pipes support.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Polling provides non-blocking synchronous API which may be used to implement some asynchronous API.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in traditional Unix and Windows.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Its major problem is that it can waste CPU time polling repeatedly when there is nothing else for the issuing process to do, reducing the time available for other processes.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Also, because a polling application is essentially single-threaded it may be unable to fully exploit I/O parallelism that the hardware is capable of.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in BSD Unix, and almost anything else with a TCP/IP protocol stack that either utilizes or is modeled after the BSD implementation.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] A variation on the theme of polling, a select loop uses the `select` system call to sleep until a condition occurs on a file descriptor (e.g., when data is available for reading), a timeout occurs, or a signal is received (e.g., when a child process dies).
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] By examining the return parameters of the `select` call, the loop finds out which file descriptor has changed and executes the appropriate code.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Often, for ease of use, the select loop is implemented as an event loop, perhaps using callback functions; the situation lends itself particularly well to event-driven programming.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] While this method is reliable and relatively efficient, it depends heavily on the Unix paradigm that "everything is a file"; any blocking I/O that does not involve a file descriptor will block the process.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The select loop also relies on being able to involve all I/O in the central `select` call; libraries that conduct their own I/O are particularly problematic in this respect.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Some Unixes provide system-specific calls with better scaling; for example, `epoll` in Linux (that fills the return selection array with only those event sources on which an event has occurred), `kqueue` in FreeBSD, and event ports (and `/dev/poll`) in Solaris.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] SVR3 Unix provided the `poll` system call.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Arguably better-named than `select`, for the purposes of this discussion it is essentially the same thing.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] SVR4 Unixes (and thus POSIX) offer both calls.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] I/O is issued asynchronously, and when it is completed a signal (interrupt) is generated.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] As in low-level kernel programming, the facilities available for safe use within the signal handler are limited, and the main flow of the process could have been interrupted at nearly any point, resulting in inconsistent data structures as seen by the signal handler.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The signal handler is usually not able to issue further asynchronous I/O by itself.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The *signal* approach, though relatively simple to implement within the OS, brings to the application program the unwelcome baggage associated with writing an operating system's kernel interrupt system.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Its worst characteristic is that *every* blocking (synchronous) system call is potentially interruptible; the programmer must usually incorporate retry code at each call.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in the classic Mac OS, VMS and Windows.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *signal* method as it is fundamentally the same thing, though rarely recognized as such.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The difference is that each I/O request usually can have its own completion function, whereas the *signal* system has a single callback.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] On the other hand, a potential problem of using callbacks is that stack depth can grow unmanageably, as an extremely common thing to do when one I/O is finished is to schedule another.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] If this should be satisfied immediately, the first callback is not 'unwound' off the stack before the next one is invoked.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Systems to prevent this (like 'mid-ground' scheduling of new work) add complexity and reduce performance.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] In practice, however, this is generally not a problem because the new I/O will itself usually return as soon as the new I/O is started allowing the stack to be 'unwound'.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The problem can also be prevented by avoiding any further callbacks, by means of a queue, until the first callback returns.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Light-weight processes (LWPs) or threads are available in most modern operating systems.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Like the *process* method, but with lower overhead and without the data isolation that hampers coordination of the flows.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Each LWP or thread itself uses traditional blocking synchronous I/O, which simplifies programming logic; this is a common paradigm used in many programming languages including Java and Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Multithreading needs to use kernel-provided synchronization mechanisms and thread-safe libraries.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This method is most suitable for extremely large-scale applications like web servers due to the large numbers of threads needed.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is also used in the Erlang programming language runtime system.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The Erlang virtual machine uses asynchronous I/O using a small pool of only a few threads or sometimes just one process, to handle I/O from up to millions of Erlang processes.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] I/O handling in each process is written mostly using blocking synchronous I/O.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This way high performance of asynchronous I/O is merged with simplicity of normal I/O (cf. the Actor model).
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Many I/O problems in Erlang are mapped to message passing, which can be easily processed using built-in selective receive.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Fibers / Coroutines can be viewed as a similarly lightweight approach to do asynchronous I/O outside of the Erlang runtime system, although they do not provide exactly the same guarantees as Erlang processes.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Microsoft Windows, Solaris, AmigaOS, DNIX and Linux (using io_uring, available on 5.1 and above).
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] I/O requests are issued asynchronously, but notifications of completion are provided via a synchronizing queue mechanism in the order they are completed.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Usually associated with a state-machine structuring of the main process (event-driven programming), which can bear little resemblance to a process that does not use asynchronous I/O or that uses one of the other forms, hampering code reuse.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Does not require additional special synchronization mechanisms or thread-safe libraries, nor are the textual (code) and time (event) flows separated.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in VMS and AmigaOS (often used in conjunction with a completion port).
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *completion queue* method, as it is essentially a completion queue of depth one.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] To simulate the effect of queue 'depth', an additional event flag is required for each potential unprocessed (but completed) event, or event information can be lost.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Waiting for the next available event in such a clump requires synchronizing mechanisms that may not scale well to larger numbers of potentially parallel events.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in mainframes by IBM, Groupe Bull, and Unisys.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Channel I/O is designed to maximize CPU utilization and throughput by offloading most I/O onto a coprocessor.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The coprocessor has onboard DMA, handles device interrupts, is controlled by the main CPU, and only interrupts the main CPU when it's truly necessary.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This architecture also supports so-called channel programs that run on the channel processor to do heavy lifting for I/O activities and protocols.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Windows Server 2012 and Windows 8.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Optimized for applications that process large numbers of small messages to achieve higher I/O operations per second with reduced jitter and latency.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The vast majority of general-purpose computing hardware relies entirely upon two methods of implementing asynchronous I/O: polling and interrupts.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Usually both methods are used together, the balance depends heavily upon the design of the hardware and its required performance characteristics.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Pure polling systems are entirely possible, small microcontrollers (such as systems using the PIC microcontroller) are often built this way.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] CP/M systems could also be built this way (though rarely were), with or without DMA.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Also, when the utmost performance is necessary for only a *few* tasks, at the expense of any other potential tasks, polling may also be appropriate as the overhead of taking interrupts may be unwelcome.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Most general-purpose computing systems rely heavily upon interrupts.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] A pure interrupt system may be possible, though usually some component of polling is also required, as it is very common for multiple potential sources of interrupts to share a common interrupt signal line, in which case polling is used within the device driver to resolve the actual source.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] (This resolution time also contributes to an interrupt system's performance penalty.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Over the years a great deal of work has been done to try to minimize the overhead associated with servicing an interrupt.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Hybrid approaches are also possible, wherein an interrupt can trigger the beginning of some burst of asynchronous I/O, and polling is used within the burst itself.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This technique is common in high-speed device drivers, such as network or disk, where the time lost in returning to the pre-interrupt task is greater than the time until the next required servicing.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] (Common I/O hardware in use these days relies heavily upon DMA and large data buffers to make up for a relatively poorly-performing interrupt system.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] These characteristically use polling inside the driver loops, and can exhibit tremendous throughput.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] At one time this sort of hybrid approach was common in disk and network drivers where there was not DMA or significant buffering available.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] (In effect using the processor itself as a DMA engine.) The 6502 processor offered an unusual means to provide a three-element per-datum loop, as it had a hardware pin that, when asserted, would cause the processor's Overflow bit to be set directly.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Using only these two tools (polling, and interrupts), all the other forms of asynchronous I/O discussed above may be (and in fact, are) synthesized.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] In an environment such as a Java virtual machine (JVM), asynchronous I/O can be synthesized *even though* the environment the JVM is running in may not offer it at all.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This is due to the interpreted nature of the JVM.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The JVM may poll (or take an interrupt) periodically to institute an internal flow of control change, effecting the appearance of multiple simultaneous processes, at least some of which presumably exist in order to perform asynchronous I/O.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] That, in fact, is the problem with using polling in any form to synthesize a different form of asynchronous I/O.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is a poll is wasted, and lost to overhead rather than accomplishing a desired task.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is *not* a poll represents an increase in latency of reaction to pending I/O.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Striking an acceptable balance between these two opposing forces is difficult.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The trick to maximize efficiency is to minimize the amount of work that has to be done upon reception of an interrupt in order to awaken the appropriate application.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Secondarily (but perhaps no less important) is the method the application itself uses to determine what it needs to do.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Particularly problematic (for application efficiency) are the exposed polling methods, including the select/poll mechanisms.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Though the underlying I/O events they are interested in are in all likelihood interrupt-driven, the interaction *to* this mechanism is polled and can consume a large amount of time in the poll.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This is particularly true of the potentially large-scale polling possible through select (and poll).
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Interrupts map very well to Signals, Callback functions, Completion Queues, and Event flags, such systems can be very efficient.
[src:tokio-async-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The following examples show three approaches to reading I/O.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] They have been described as "functions whose execution you can pause".
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Melvin Conway coined the term *coroutine* in 1958 when he applied it to the construction of an assembly program.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] The first published explanation of the coroutine appeared later, in 1963.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] There is no single precise definition of coroutine.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] 2. the execution of a coroutine is suspended as control leaves it, only to carry on where it left off when control re-enters the coroutine at some later stage.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] 3. whether a coroutine is able to suspend its execution from within nested function calls.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Such a coroutine is a *stackful coroutine*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] One to the contrary is called *stackless coroutines*, where unless marked as coroutine, a regular function can't use the keyword `yield`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] The paper "Revisiting Coroutines" published in 2009 proposed the term *full coroutine* to denote one that supports first-class coroutine and is stackful.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Full Coroutines deserve their own name in that they have the same expressive power as one-shot continuations and delimited continuations.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Full coroutines are either symmetric or asymmetric.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Importantly, whether a coroutine is symmetric or asymmetric has no bearing on how expressive it can be, though full coroutines are more expressive than non-full coroutines.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] While their expressive power is the same, asymmetrical coroutines more closely resemble routine based control structures in the sense that control is always passed back to the invoker, which programmers may find more familiar.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Subroutines are special cases of coroutines.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] When subroutines are invoked, execution begins at the start, and once a subroutine exits, it is finished; an instance of a subroutine only returns once, and does not hold state between invocations.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] By contrast, coroutines can exit by calling other coroutines, which may later return to the point where they were invoked in the original coroutine; from the coroutine's point of view, it is not exiting but calling another coroutine.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Thus, a coroutine instance holds state, and varies between invocations; there can be multiple instances of a given coroutine at once.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] The difference between calling another coroutine by means of "yielding" to it and simply calling another routine (which then, also, would return to the original point), is that the relationship between two coroutines which yield to each other is not that of caller-callee, but instead symmetric.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Any subroutine can be translated to a coroutine which does not call *yield*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Here is a simple example of how coroutines can be useful.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Suppose you have a consumer-producer relationship where one routine creates items and adds them to a queue and another removes items from the queue and uses them.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] For reasons of efficiency, you want to add and remove several items at once.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] The queue is then completely filled or emptied before yielding control to the other coroutine using the *yield* command.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] The further coroutines calls are starting right after the *yield*, in the outer coroutine loop.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Although this example is often used as an introduction to multithreading, two threads are not needed for this: the *yield* statement can be implemented by a jump directly from one routine into the other.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] However, coroutines are cooperatively multitasked, whereas threads are typically preemptively multitasked.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Coroutines provide concurrency, because they allow tasks to be performed out of order or in a changeable order, without changing the overall outcome, but they do not provide parallelism, because they do not execute multiple tasks simultaneously.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] It is possible to implement coroutines using preemptively-scheduled threads, in a way that will be transparent to the calling code, but some of the advantages (particularly the suitability for hard-realtime operation and relative cheapness of switching between them) will be lost.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Generators, also known as semicoroutines, are a subset of coroutines.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] That is, since generators are primarily used to simplify the writing of iterators, the `yield` statement in a generator does not specify a coroutine to jump to, but rather passes a value back to a parent routine.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] A number of implementations of coroutines for languages with generator support but no native coroutines (e.g.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Python before 2.5) use this or a similar model.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Using coroutines for state machines or concurrency is similar to using mutual recursion with tail calls, as in both cases the control changes to a different one of a set of routines.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] However, coroutines are more flexible and generally more efficient.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Further, each mutually recursive call of a subroutine requires a new stack frame (unless tail call elimination is implemented), while passing control between coroutines uses the existing contexts and can be implemented simply by a jump.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Coroutines originated as an assembly language method, but are supported in some high-level programming languages.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Java does not have native or library support for coroutines, but it can call Kotlin coroutines `kotlinx.coroutines` (though this is not ideal and would require a Java wrapper over Kotlin).
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Since continuations can be used to implement coroutines, programming languages that support them can also quite easily support coroutines.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] As of 2003, many of the most popular programming languages, including C and its derivatives, do not have built-in support for coroutines within the language or their standard libraries.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] This is, in large part, due to the limitations of stack-based subroutine implementation.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] An exception is the C++ library Boost.Context, part of Boost, which supports context swapping on ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, SPARC and x86 on POSIX, Mac OS X and Windows.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Coroutines can be built upon Boost.Context.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Conditionals within the code result in the execution of different code paths on successive calls, based on the values of the state variables.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Another typical response is to implement an explicit state machine in the form of a large and complex switch statement or via a goto statement, particularly a computed goto.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Such implementations are considered difficult to understand and maintain, and a motivation for coroutine support.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Threads, and to a lesser extent fibers, are an alternative to coroutines in mainstream programming environments today.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Threads provide facilities for managing the real-time cooperative interaction of *simultaneously* executing pieces of code.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Threads are widely available in environments that support C (and are supported natively in many other modern languages), are familiar to many programmers, and are usually well-implemented, well-documented and well-supported.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] However, as they solve a large and difficult problem they include many powerful and complex facilities and have a correspondingly difficult learning curve.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] As such, when a coroutine is all that is needed, using a thread can be overkill.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] One important difference between threads and coroutines is that threads are typically preemptively scheduled while coroutines are not.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Because threads can be rescheduled at any instant and can execute concurrently, programs using threads must be careful about locking.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] In contrast, because coroutines can only be rescheduled at specific points in the program and do not execute concurrently, programs using coroutines can often avoid locking entirely.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] This property is also cited as a benefit of event-driven or asynchronous programming.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Since fibers are cooperatively scheduled, they provide an ideal base for implementing coroutines above.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] However, system support for fibers is often lacking compared to that for threads.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] In order to implement general-purpose coroutines, a second call stack must be obtained, which is a feature not directly supported by the C language.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] A reliable (albeit platform-specific) way to achieve this is to use a small amount of inline assembly to explicitly manipulate the stack pointer during initial creation of the coroutine.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] This is the approach recommended by Tom Duff in a discussion on its relative merits vs. the method used by Protothreads.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] On platforms which provide the POSIX sigaltstack system call, a second call stack can be obtained by calling a springboard function from within a signal handler to achieve the same goal in portable C, at the cost of some extra complexity.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] C libraries complying to POSIX or the Single Unix Specification (SUSv3) provided such routines as getcontext, setcontext, makecontext and swapcontext, but these functions were declared obsolete in POSIX 1.2008.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Once a second call stack has been obtained with one of the methods listed above, the setjmp and longjmp functions in the standard C library can then be used to implement the switches between coroutines.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] These functions save and restore, respectively, the stack pointer, program counter, callee-saved registers, and any other internal state as required by the ABI, such that returning to a coroutine after having yielded restores all the state that would be restored upon returning from a function call.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Minimalist implementations, which do not piggyback off the setjmp and longjmp functions, may achieve the same result via a small block of inline assembly which swaps merely the stack pointer and program counter, and clobbers all other registers.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] This can be significantly faster, as setjmp and longjmp must conservatively store all registers which may be in use according to the ABI, whereas the clobber method allows the compiler to store (by spilling to the stack) only what it knows is actually in use.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Due to the lack of direct language support, many authors have written their own libraries for coroutines which hide the above details.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Russ Cox's libtask library is a good example of this genre.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] It uses the context functions if they are provided by the native C library; otherwise it provides its own implementations for ARM, PowerPC, Sparc, and x86.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Other notable implementations include libpcl, coro, lthread, libCoroutine, libconcurrency, libcoro, ribs2, libdill., libaco, and libco.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] In addition to the general approach above, several attempts have been made to approximate coroutines in C with combinations of subroutines and macros.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Simon Tatham's contribution, based on Duff's device, is a notable example of the genre, and is the basis for Protothreads and similar implementations.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] C++20 introduced standardized coroutines as stackless functions that can be suspended in the middle of execution and resumed at a later point.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] The suspended state of a coroutine is stored on the heap.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Implementation of this standard is ongoing, with the G++ and MSVC compilers currently fully supporting standard coroutines in recent versions.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] A generator class for synchronous and lazy-evaluated ranges, `std::generator`, was added in C++23.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] It is invoked using `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] This is an example of C++20 coroutines with the C++26 `std::execution::task` class.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] C# 2.0 added semi-coroutine (generator) functionality through the iterator pattern and `yield` keyword.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Cloroutine is a third-party library providing support for stackless coroutines in Clojure.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] It's implemented as a macro, statically splitting an arbitrary code block on arbitrary var calls and emitting the coroutine as a stateful function.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] D implements coroutines as its standard library class `core.thread.Fiber` for a fiber.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] A generator (`std.concurrency.Generator`) makes it trivial to expose a fiber function as an input range (`std.range.interfaces.InputRange`), making any fiber compatible with existing range algorithms.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Go has a built-in concept of "goroutines", a type of green thread which are lightweight, independent processes managed by the Go runtime.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] A new goroutine can be started using the "go" keyword.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Each goroutine has a variable-size stack which can be expanded as needed.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Goroutines generally communicate using Go's built-in channels.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] However, goroutines are not coroutines (for instance, local data does not persist between successive calls).
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] There are several implementations for coroutines in Java.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Despite the constraints imposed by Java's abstractions, the JVM does not preclude the possibility.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] There are four general methods used, but two break bytecode portability among standards-compliant JVMs.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Since ECMAScript 2015, JavaScript has support for generators, which are a special case of coroutines.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Kotlin implements coroutines as part of a first-party library.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Lua has supported first-class stackful asymmetric coroutines since version 5.0 (2003), in the standard library *coroutine*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] Modula-2 as defined by Wirth implements coroutines as part of the standard SYSTEM library.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] The procedure NEWPROCESS() fills in a context given a code block and space for a stack as parameters, and the procedure TRANSFER() transfers control to a coroutine given the coroutine's context as its parameter.
[src:tokio-async-rust/coroutine] The Mono Common Language Runtime has support for continuations, from which coroutines can be built.
