[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In software, an **event loop** is an algorithm that continually dispatches control flow for events.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] The loop requests the next event from an event provider (which generally blocks the loop until an event occurs), and when an event is received, invokes its associated event handler.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] When the event loop is the central event dispatcher of a program, as it often is, it is called the **main loop** or **main event loop**.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In modern environments such as web browsers and server runtimes, the event loop is a fundamental mechanism that enables asynchronous execution by continuously monitoring and dispatching events or messages from a queue when the main program thread is idle.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In JavaScript, the event loop allows non-blocking handling of tasks such as user interactions, timers, and I/O operations despite the language being single-threaded.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] The same algorithm can be used to process inbound messages, a superset of events.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In this context, the algorithm is called a **message loop**, **message dispatcher**, or **message pump**.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] A common use for a message loop is message passing inter-process communication where the message queue is maintained outside of the program (such as by the operating system).
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Typically, a program that operates in a graphical user interface (GUI) environment uses an event loop, and due to the predominance of GUI environments, most modern applications have a main event loop.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In the following pseudocode, `get_next_message()` is a placeholder for a function that is typically provided by the operating system that blocks until a message is available.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Thus, the loop only repeats when there is a message to process.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Many programs include an event loop in the high-level design; a main event loop, but there are alternative designs.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] A program can exit as soon as it completes the actions that it's designed to do without external (i.e. user) interaction.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Often, such a program has optional behavior that is set up before the program starts such as via the command-line interface (CLI) or environment variables.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Utility software is often of this nature.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Even if a program provides for user interaction, it might not use an event loop.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] A program that provides an internal CLI does include a command processor that is similar to an event loop in that it dispatches to command handlers based on user input.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] A web page and its JavaScript typically run in a single-threaded web browser process.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] The browser process deals with messages from a queue one at a time.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] A JavaScript function or another browser event might be associated with a given message.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] When the browser process has finished with a message, it proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In JavaScript environments, the event loop works with separate queues — including a task queue and a microtask queue — to manage asynchronous operations such as timers, promise callbacks, and DOM events.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] When the call stack is empty, the event loop selects the next task from these queues to execute.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In Windows, a process that interacts with the user must accept and react to incoming messages, which is almost inevitably done by a message loop in that process.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In Windows, a message is equated to an event created and imposed upon the operating system.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] An event can be user interaction, network traffic, system processing, timer activity, inter-process communication, among others.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] For non-interactive, I/O only events, Windows has I/O completion ports.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] I/O completion port loops run separately from the Message loop, and do not interact with the Message loop out of the box.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] The heart of most Win32 applications is the WinMain() function, which calls GetMessage() in a loop.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] GetMessage() blocks until a message (event), is received (with function PeekMessage() as a non-blocking alternative).
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] After some optional processing, it will call DispatchMessage(), which dispatches the message to the relevant handler, also known as WindowProc.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Normally, messages that have no special WindowProc() are dispatched to DefWindowProc, the default one.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] DispatchMessage() calls the WindowProc of the HWND handle of the message (registered with the RegisterClass() function).
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] More recent versions of Windows guarantee that messages will be delivered to an application's message loop in the order that they were perceived by the system and its peripherals.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] This guarantee is essential when considering the design consequences of multithreaded applications.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] However, some messages have different rules, such as messages that are always received last, or messages with a different documented priority.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] X applications using Xlib directly are built around the `XNextEvent` family of functions; `XNextEvent` blocks until an event appears on the event queue, whereupon the application processes it appropriately.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] The Xlib event loop only handles window system events; applications that need to be able to wait on other files and devices could construct their own event loop from primitives such as `ConnectionNumber`, but in practice tend to use multithreading.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In the more common case, GUI toolkits based on Xlib usually support adding events.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] For example, toolkits based on Xt Intrinsics have `XtAppAddInput()` and `XtAppAddTimeout()`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] It is not safe to call Xlib functions from a signal handler, because the X application may have been interrupted in an arbitrary state, e.g. within `XNextEvent`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] See [1] for a solution for X11R5, X11R6 and Xt.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] The GLib event loop was originally created for use in GTK but is now used in non-GUI applications as well, such as D-Bus.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] The resource polled is the collection of file descriptors the application is interested in; the polling block will be interrupted if a signal arrives or a timeout expires (e.g. if the application has specified a timeout or idle task).
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Application libraries that are built on the GLib event loop include GStreamer and the asynchronous I/O methods of GnomeVFS, but GTK remains the most visible client library.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Events from the windowing system (in X, read off the X socket) are translated by GDK into GTK events and emitted as GLib signals on the application's widget objects.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Exactly one CFRunLoop is allowed per thread, and arbitrarily many sources and observers can be attached.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Sources then communicate with observers through the run loop, with it organising queueing and dispatch of messages.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] The CFRunLoop is abstracted in Cocoa as an NSRunLoop, which allows any message (equivalent to a function call in non-reflective runtimes) to be queued for dispatch to any object.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In Unix, the everything is a file paradigm leads to a file-based event loop.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Reading from and writing to files, inter-process communication, network communication, and device control are all achieved using file I/O, with the target identified by a file descriptor.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] The select and poll system calls allow a set of file descriptors to be monitored for a change of state, e.g. when data becomes available to be read.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In Unix, a signal is an asynchronous event that is handled by a signal handler which runs while the rest of the task is suspended.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] If a signal is received and handled while the task is blocking in `select()`, select will return early with EINTR; if a signal is received while the task is CPU bound, the task will be suspended between instructions until the signal handler returns.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] A way to handle a signal is for signal handlers to set a global flag and have the event loop check for the flag immediately before and after the `select()` call; if it is set, handle the signal in the same manner as with events on file descriptors.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Unfortunately, this gives rise to a race condition: if a signal arrives immediately between checking the flag and calling `select()`, it will not be handled until `select()` returns for some other reason (for example, being interrupted by a frustrated user).
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] The solution arrived at by POSIX is the `pselect()` call, which is similar to `select()` but takes an additional `sigmask` parameter, which describes a *signal mask*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] This allows an application to mask signals in the main task, then remove the mask for the duration of the `select()` call such that signal handlers are only called while the application is I/O bound.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] However, implementations of `pselect()` have not always been reliable; versions of Linux prior to 2.6.16 do not have a `pselect()` system call, forcing glibc to emulate it via a method prone to the very same race condition `pselect()` is intended to avoid.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] An alternative, more portable solution, is to convert asynchronous events to file-based events using the *self-pipe trick*, where "a signal handler writes a byte to a pipe whose other end is monitored by `select()` in the main program".
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In Linux kernel version 2.6.22, a new system call `signalfd()` was added, which allows receiving signals via a special file descriptor.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] In environments such as web browsers and Node.js, the event loop is central to asynchronous program behavior.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] JavaScript runs on a single thread for execution, but host environments provide APIs for non-blocking operations, such as timers, network requests, and user events.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] Completed asynchronous operations are placed in queues, and the event loop repeatedly checks whether the call stack is empty to schedule queued callbacks.
[src:tokio-async-rust/event-loop] This enables JavaScript applications to remain responsive while handling multiple asynchronous tasks.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] In computer science, **futures**, **promises**, **delays**, and **deferreds** are constructs used for synchronizing program execution in some concurrent programming languages.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Each is an object that acts as a proxy for a result that is initially unknown, usually because the computation of its value is not yet complete.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was proposed in 1976 by Daniel P.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Friedman and David Wise, and Peter Hibbard called it *eventual*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] A somewhat similar concept *future* was introduced in 1977 in a paper by Henry Baker and Carl Hewitt.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The terms *future*, *promise*, *delay*, and *deferred* are often used interchangeably, although there can be some differences in usage between *future* and *promise*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Specifically, when usage is distinguished, a future is a *read-only* placeholder view of a variable, while a promise is a writable, single assignment container which sets the value of the future.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Notably, a future may be defined without specifying which specific promise will set its value, and different possible promises may set the value of a given future, though this can be done only once for a given future.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] In other cases a future and a promise are created together and associated with each other: the future is the value, the promise is the function that sets the value – essentially the return value (future) of an asynchronous function (promise).
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Setting the value of a future is also called *resolving*, *fulfilling*, or *binding* it.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Futures and promises originated in functional programming and related paradigms (such as logic programming) to decouple a value (a future) from how it was computed (a promise), allowing the computation to be done more flexibly, notably by parallelizing it.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Later, it found use in distributed computing, in reducing the latency from communication round trips.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Later still, it gained more use by allowing writing asynchronous programs in direct style, rather than in continuation-passing style.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Use of futures may be *implicit* (any use of the future automatically obtains its value, as if it were an ordinary reference) or *explicit* (the user must call a function to obtain the value, such as the `get` method of `java.util.concurrent.Future`in Java).
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Obtaining the value of an explicit future can be called *stinging* or *forcing*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Explicit futures can be implemented as a library, whereas implicit futures are usually implemented as part of the language.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The original Baker and Hewitt paper described implicit futures, which are naturally supported in the actor model of computation and pure object-oriented programming languages like Smalltalk.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The Friedman and Wise paper described only explicit futures, probably reflecting the difficulty of efficiently implementing implicit futures on stock hardware.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The difficulty is that stock hardware does not deal with futures for primitive data types like integers.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] For example, an add instruction does not know how to deal with `3 + *future* factorial(100000)`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] In pure actor or object languages this problem can be solved by sending `*future* factorial(100000)` the message `+[3]`, which asks the future to add `3` to itself and return the result.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Note that the message passing approach works regardless of when `factorial(100000)` finishes computation and that no stinging/forcing is needed.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The use of futures can dramatically reduce latency in distributed systems.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] For instance, futures enable *promise pipelining*, as implemented in the languages E and Joule, which was also called *call-stream* in the language Argus.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Each statement needs a message to be sent and a reply received before the next statement can proceed.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Suppose, for example, that `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] In this case, two complete network round-trips to that machine must take place before the third statement can begin to execute.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The third statement will then cause yet another round-trip to the same remote machine.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The syntax used here is that of the language E, where `x <- a()` means to send the message `a()` asynchronously to `x`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] All three variables are immediately assigned futures for their results, and execution proceeds to subsequent statements.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Later attempts to resolve the value of `t3` may cause a delay; however, pipelining can reduce the number of round-trips needed.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] If, as in the prior example, `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine, a pipelined implementation can compute `t3` with one round-trip instead of three.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Because all three messages are destined for objects which are on the same remote machine, only one request need be sent and only one response need be received containing the result.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The send `t1 <- c(t2)` would not block even if `t1` and `t2` were on different machines to each other, or to `x` or `y`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining should be distinguished from parallel asynchronous message passing.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The relative latency advantage of pipelining becomes even greater in more complicated situations involving many messages.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining also should not be confused with pipelined message processing in actor systems, where it is possible for an actor to specify and begin executing a behaviour for the next message before having completed processing of the current message.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Support for read-only views is consistent with the principle of least privilege, since it enables the ability to set the value to be restricted to subjects that need to set it.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] In a system that also supports pipelining, the sender of an asynchronous message (with result) receives the read-only promise for the result, and the target of the message receives the resolver.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Some languages, such as Alice ML, define futures that are associated with a specific thread that computes the future's value.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] This computation can start either eagerly when the future is created, or lazily when its value is first needed.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] A lazy future is similar to a thunk, in the sense of a delayed computation.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Alice ML also supports futures that can be resolved by any thread, and calls these *promises*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] This use of *promise* is different from its use in E as described above.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] In Alice, a promise is not a read-only view, and promise pipelining is unsupported.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Instead, pipelining naturally happens for futures, including ones associated with promises.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] If the value of a future is accessed asynchronously, for example by sending a message to it, or by explicitly waiting for it using a construct such as `when` in E, then there is no difficulty in delaying until the future is resolved before the message can be received or the wait completes.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] This is the only case to be considered in purely asynchronous systems such as pure actor languages.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] However, in some systems it may also be possible to attempt to *immediately* or *synchronously* access a future's value.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] As an example of the first possibility, in C++11, a thread that needs the value of a future can block until it is available by calling the `wait()` or `get()` member functions.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] A timeout can also be specified on the wait using the `wait_for()` or `wait_until()` member functions to avoid indefinite blocking.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] If the future arose from a call to `std::async` then a blocking wait (without a timeout) may cause synchronous invocation of the function to compute the result on the waiting thread.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] An *I-var* (as in the language Id) is a future with blocking semantics as defined above.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] An *I-structure* is a data structure containing I-vars.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] A related synchronization construct that can be set multiple times with different values is called an *M-var*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] M-vars support atomic operations to *take* or *put* the current value, where taking the value also sets the M-var back to its initial *empty* state.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent logic variable* is similar to a future, but is updated by unification, in the same way as *logic variables* in logic programming.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Thus it can be bound more than once to unifiable values, but cannot be set back to an empty or unresolved state.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The dataflow variables of Oz act as concurrent logic variables, and also have blocking semantics as mentioned above.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent constraint variable* is a generalization of concurrent logic variables to support constraint logic programming: the constraint may be *narrowed* multiple times, indicating smaller sets of possible values.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Typically there is a way to specify a thunk that should run whenever the constraint is narrowed further; this is needed to support *constraint propagation*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Eager thread-specific futures can be straightforwardly implemented in non-thread-specific futures, by creating a thread to calculate the value at the same time as creating the future.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] In this case it is desirable to return a read-only view to the client, so that only the newly created thread is able to resolve this future.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] To implement implicit lazy thread-specific futures (as provided by Alice ML, for example) in terms in non-thread-specific futures, needs a mechanism to determine when the future's value is first needed (for example, the `WaitNeeded` construct in Oz).
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] If all values are objects, then the ability to implement transparent forwarding objects is sufficient, since the first message sent to the forwarder indicates that the future's value is needed.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Non-thread-specific futures can be implemented in thread-specific futures, assuming that the system supports message passing, by having the resolving thread send a message to the future's own thread.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] However, this can be viewed as unneeded complexity.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] In programming languages based on threads, the most expressive approach seems to be to provide a mix of non-thread-specific futures, read-only views, and either a *WaitNeeded* construct, or support for transparent forwarding.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The evaluation strategy of futures, which may be termed *call by future*, is non-deterministic: the value of a future will be evaluated at some time between when the future is created and when its value is used, but the precise time is not determined beforehand and can change from run to run.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The computation can start as soon as the future is created (eager evaluation) or only when the value is actually needed (lazy evaluation), and may be suspended part-way through, or executed in one run.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Once the value of a future is assigned, it is not recomputed on future accesses; this is like the memoization used in call by need.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] A **lazy future** is a future that deterministically has lazy evaluation semantics: the computation of the future's value starts when the value is first needed, as in call by need.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Lazy futures are of use in languages which evaluation strategy is by default not lazy.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] For example, in C++11 such lazy futures can be created by passing the `std::launch::deferred` launch policy to `std::async`, along with the function to compute the value.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] If it does not already have a response, then *R* is stored in the queue of requests inside the *F*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] However, some futures can deal with requests in special ways to provide greater parallelism.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] For example, the expression `1 + future factorial(n)` can create a new future that will behave like the number `1+factorial(n)`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] suspends until the future for `factorial(n)` has responded to the request asking if `m` is greater than itself.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The *future* and/or *promise* constructs were first implemented in programming languages such as MultiLisp and Act 1.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The use of logic variables for communication in concurrent logic programming languages was quite similar to futures.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] These began in *Prolog with Freeze* and *IC Prolog*, and became a true concurrency primitive with Relational Language, Concurrent Prolog, guarded Horn clauses (GHC), Parlog, Strand, Vulcan, Janus, Oz-Mozart, Flow Java, and Alice ML.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The single-assignment *I-var* from dataflow programming languages, originating in Id and included in Reppy's *Concurrent ML*, is much like the concurrent logic variable.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The promise pipelining technique (using futures to overcome latency) was invented by Barbara Liskov and Liuba Shrira in 1988, and independently by Mark S.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Miller, Dean Tribble and Rob Jellinghaus in the context of Project Xanadu circa 1989.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was coined by Liskov and Shrira, although they referred to the pipelining mechanism by the name *call-stream*, which is now rarely used.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] It seems that promises and call-streams were never implemented in any public release of Argus, the programming language used in the Liskov and Shrira paper.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The Xanadu implementation of promise pipelining only became publicly available with the release of the source code for Udanax Gold in 1999, and was never explained in any published document.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The later implementations in Joule and E support fully first-class promises and resolvers.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Several early actor languages, including the Act series, supported both parallel message passing and pipelined message processing, but not promise pipelining.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] After 2000, a major revival of interest in futures and promises occurred, due to their use in responsiveness of user interfaces, and in web development, due to the request–response model of message-passing.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] This has subsequently been adopted by other languages, notably Dart (2014), Python (2015), Hack (HHVM), and drafts of ECMAScript 7 (JavaScript), Scala, and C++ (2011).
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Some programming languages are supporting futures, promises, concurrent logic variables, dataflow variables, or I-vars, either by direct language support or in the standard library.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Futures can be implemented in coroutines or generators, resulting in the same evaluation strategy (e.g., cooperative multitasking or lazy evaluation).
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] Futures can easily be implemented in channels: a future is a one-element channel, and a promise is a process that sends to the channel, fulfilling the future.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] This allows futures to be implemented in concurrent programming languages with support for channels, such as CSP and Go.
[src:tokio-async-rust/futures-and-promises] The resulting futures are explicit, as they must be accessed by reading from the channel, rather than only evaluation.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] In computer programming, a **green thread** is a thread that is scheduled by a runtime library or virtual machine (VM) instead of natively by the underlying operating system (OS).
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] Green threads emulate multithreaded environments without relying on any native OS abilities, and they are managed in user space instead of kernel space, enabling them to work in environments that do not have native thread support.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] Green threads refers to the name of the original thread library for Java programming language (that was released in version 1.1 and then Green threads were abandoned in version 1.3 to native threads).
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] It was designed by *The Green Team* at Sun Microsystems.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] Green threads were briefly available in Java between 1997 and 2000.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] Green threads share a single operating system thread through co-operative concurrency and can therefore not achieve parallelism performance gains like operating system threads.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] The main benefit of coroutines and green threads is ease of implementation.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] On a multi-core processor, native thread implementations can automatically assign work to multiple processors, whereas green thread implementations normally cannot.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] Green threads can be started much faster on some VMs.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] On uniprocessor computers, however, the most efficient model has not yet been clearly determined.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] When a green thread executes a blocking system call, not only is that thread blocked, but all of the threads within the process are blocked.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] To avoid that problem, green threads must use non-blocking I/O or asynchronous I/O operations, although the increased complexity on the user side can be reduced if the virtual machine implementing the green threads spawns specific I/O processes (hidden to the user) for each I/O operation.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] In Java 1.1, green threads were the only threading model used by the Java virtual machine (JVM), at least on Solaris.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] As green threads have some limitations compared to native threads, subsequent Java versions dropped them in favor of native threads.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] An exception to this is the Squawk virtual machine, which is a mixture between an operating system for low-power devices and a Java virtual machine.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] It uses green threads to minimize the use of native code, and to support migrating its isolates.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] Kilim and Quasar are open-source projects which implement green threads on later versions of the JVM by modifying the Java bytecode produced by the Java compiler (Quasar also supports Kotlin and Clojure).
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] There are some other programming languages that implement equivalents of green threads instead of native threads.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] The Erlang virtual machine has what might be called *green processes* – they are like operating system processes (they do not share state like threads do) but are implemented within the Erlang Run Time System (erts).
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] These are sometimes termed *green threads*, but have significant differences from standard green threads.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] In the case of GHC Haskell, a context switch occurs at the first allocation after a configurable timeout.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] Most Smalltalk virtual machines do not count evaluation steps; however, the VM can still preempt the executing thread on external signals (such as expiring timers, or I/O becoming available).
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] Other implementations, e.g., QKS Smalltalk, are always time-sharing.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] Unlike most green thread implementations, QKS also supports preventing priority inversion.
[src:tokio-async-rust/green-thread] Virtual threads were introduced as a preview feature in Java 19 and stabilized in Java 21.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] A runtime for writing reliable network applications without compromising speed.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Tokio is an event-driven, non-blocking I/O platform for writing asynchronous applications with the Rust programming language.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Guide level documentation is found on the website.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Tokio consists of a number of modules that provide a range of functionality essential for implementing asynchronous applications in Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] In this section, we will take a brief tour of Tokio, summarizing the major APIs and their uses.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] The easiest way to get started is to enable all features.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Tokio is great for writing applications and most users in this case shouldn’t worry too much about what features they should pick.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] If you’re unsure, we suggest going with `full` to ensure that you don’t run into any road blocks while you’re building your application.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] This example shows the quickest way to get started with Tokio.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] As a library author your goal should be to provide the lightest weight crate that is based on Tokio.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] To achieve this you should ensure that you only enable the features you need.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] This allows users to pick up your crate without having to enable unnecessary features.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] This example shows how you may want to import features for a library that just needs to `tokio::spawn` and use a `TcpStream`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Asynchronous programs in Rust are based around lightweight, non-blocking units of execution called *tasks*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] The `tokio::task` module is present only when the “rt” feature flag is enabled.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] The `tokio::sync` module contains synchronization primitives to use when needing to communicate or share data.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] The `tokio::sync` module is present only when the “sync” feature flag is enabled.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] The `tokio::time` module provides utilities for tracking time and scheduling work.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] This includes functions for setting timeouts for tasks, sleeping work to run in the future, or repeating an operation at an interval.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] In order to use `tokio::time`, the “time” feature flag must be enabled.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Finally, Tokio provides a *runtime* for executing asynchronous tasks.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Most applications can use the `#[tokio::main]` macro to run their code on the Tokio runtime.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] However, this macro provides only basic configuration options.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] As an alternative, the `tokio::runtime` module provides more powerful APIs for configuring and managing runtimes.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] You should use that module if the `#[tokio::main]` macro doesn’t provide the functionality you need.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Using the runtime requires the “rt” or “rt-multi-thread” feature flags, to enable the current-thread single-threaded scheduler and the multi-thread scheduler, respectively.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] See the `runtime` module documentation for details.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] In addition, the “macros” feature flag enables the `#[tokio::main]` and `#[tokio::test]` attributes.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Tokio is able to concurrently run many tasks on a few threads by repeatedly swapping the currently running task on each thread.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] However, this kind of swapping can only happen at `.await` points, so code that spends a long time without reaching an `.await` will prevent other tasks from running.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] To combat this, Tokio provides two kinds of threads: Core threads and blocking threads.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] The core threads are where all asynchronous code runs, and Tokio will by default spawn one for each CPU core.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] You can use the environment variable `TOKIO_WORKER_THREADS` to override the default value.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] The blocking threads are spawned on demand, can be used to run blocking code that would otherwise block other tasks from running and are kept alive when not used for a certain amount of time which can be configured with `thread_keep_alive`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Since it is not possible for Tokio to swap out blocking tasks, like it can do with asynchronous code, the upper limit on the number of blocking threads is very large.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] These limits can be configured on the `Builder`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] To spawn a blocking task, you should use the `spawn_blocking` function.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] If your code is CPU-bound and you wish to limit the number of threads used to run it, you should use a separate thread pool dedicated to CPU bound tasks.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] For example, you could consider using the rayon library for CPU-bound tasks.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] It is also possible to create an extra Tokio runtime dedicated to CPU-bound tasks, but if you do this, you should be careful that the extra runtime runs *only* CPU-bound tasks, as IO-bound tasks on that runtime will behave poorly.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Hint: If using rayon, you can use a `oneshot` channel to send the result back to Tokio when the rayon task finishes.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] As well as scheduling and running tasks, Tokio provides everything you need to perform input and output asynchronously.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] The `tokio::io` module provides Tokio’s asynchronous core I/O primitives, the `AsyncRead`, `AsyncWrite`, and `AsyncBufRead` traits.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] In addition, when the “io-util” feature flag is enabled, it also provides combinators and functions for working with these traits, forming as an asynchronous counterpart to `std::io`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Tokio also includes APIs for performing various kinds of I/O and interacting with the operating system asynchronously.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Tokio uses a set of feature flags to reduce the amount of compiled code.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] It is possible to just enable certain features over others.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] By default, Tokio does not enable any features but allows one to enable a subset for their use case.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Below is a list of the available feature flags.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] You may also notice above each function, struct and trait there is listed one or more feature flags that are required for that item to be used.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] If you are new to Tokio it is recommended that you use the `full` feature flag which will enable all public APIs.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Beware though that this will pull in many extra dependencies that you may not need.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Likewise, this flag enables access to unstable APIs.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] This flag enables **unstable** features.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] The public API of these features may break in 1.x releases.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] To enable these features, the `--cfg tokio_unstable` argument must be passed to `rustc` when compiling.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] This serves to explicitly opt-in to features which may break semver conventions, since Cargo does not yet directly support such opt-ins.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Tokio will continue to support these platforms in the future.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] However, future releases may change requirements such as the minimum required libc version on Linux, the API level on Android, or the supported FreeBSD release.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Beyond the above platforms, Tokio is intended to work on all platforms supported by the mio crate.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] You can find a longer list in mio’s documentation.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] However, these additional platforms may become unsupported in the future.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Note that Wine is considered to be a different platform from Windows.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] See mio’s documentation for more information on Wine support.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Tokio has some limited support for the `WASM` platform.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Enabling any other feature (including `full`) will cause a compilation failure.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] The `time` module will only work on `WASM` platforms that have support for timers (e.g. wasm32-wasi).
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] The timing functions will panic if used on a `WASM` platform that does not support timers.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Note also that if the runtime becomes indefinitely idle, it will panic immediately instead of blocking forever.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] On platforms that don’t support time, this means that the runtime can never be idle in any way.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Tokio also has unstable support for some additional `WASM` features.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] This requires the use of the `tokio_unstable` flag.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Using this flag enables the use of `tokio::net` on the wasm32-wasi target.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] However, not all methods are available on the networking types as `WASI` currently does not support the creation of new sockets from within `WASM`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Because of this, sockets must currently be created via the `FromRawFd` trait.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Types which are documented locally in the Tokio crate, but does not actually live here.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Traits, helpers, and type definitions for asynchronous I/O functionality.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] An implementation of asynchronous process management for Tokio.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Synchronization primitives for use in asynchronous contexts.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] branch completes, cancelling the remaining branches.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Marks async function to be executed by the selected runtime.
[src:tokio-async-rust/latest-tokio] Marks async function to be executed by runtime, suitable to test environment.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] In computer science, an algorithm is called **non-blocking** if failure or suspension of any thread cannot cause failure or suspension of another thread; for some operations, these algorithms provide a useful alternative to traditional blocking implementations.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] A non-blocking algorithm is **lock-free** if there is guaranteed system-wide progress, and **wait-free** if there is also guaranteed per-thread progress.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] "Non-blocking" was used as a synonym for "lock-free" in the literature until the introduction of obstruction-freedom in 2003.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] The word "non-blocking" was traditionally used to describe telecommunications networks that could route a connection through a set of relays "without having to re-arrange existing calls" (see Clos network).
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Also, if the telephone exchange "is not defective, it can always make the connection" (see nonblocking minimal spanning switch).
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] The traditional approach to multi-threaded programming is to use locks to synchronize access to shared resources.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Synchronization primitives such as mutexes, semaphores, and critical sections are all mechanisms by which a programmer can ensure that certain sections of code do not execute concurrently, if doing so could corrupt shared memory structures.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] If one thread attempts to acquire a lock that is already held by another thread, the thread will block until the lock is free.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Blocking a thread can be undesirable for many reasons.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] An obvious reason is that while the thread is blocked, it cannot accomplish anything: if the blocked thread had been performing a high-priority or real-time task, it would be highly undesirable to halt its progress.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] For example, certain interactions between locks can lead to error conditions such as deadlock, livelock, and priority inversion.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Using locks also involves a trade-off between coarse-grained locking, which can significantly reduce opportunities for parallelism, and fine-grained locking, which requires more careful design, increases locking overhead and is more prone to bugs.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Unlike blocking algorithms, non-blocking algorithms do not suffer from these downsides, and in addition are safe for use in interrupt handlers: even though the preempted thread cannot be resumed, progress is still possible without it.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] In contrast, global data structures protected by mutual exclusion cannot safely be accessed in an interrupt handler, as the preempted thread may be the one holding the lock.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] While this can be rectified by masking interrupt requests during the critical section, this requires the code in the critical section to have bounded (and preferably short) running time, or excessive interrupt latency may be observed.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] A lock-free data structure can be used to improve performance.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] A lock-free data structure increases the amount of time spent in parallel execution rather than serial execution, improving performance on a multi-core processor, because access to the shared data structure does not need to be serialized to stay coherent.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] With few exceptions, non-blocking algorithms use atomic read-modify-write primitives that the hardware must provide, the most notable of which is compare and swap (CAS).
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Critical sections are almost always implemented using standard interfaces over these primitives (in the general case, critical sections will be blocking, even when implemented with these primitives).
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] In the 1990s all non-blocking algorithms had to be written "natively" with the underlying primitives to achieve acceptable performance.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] However, the emerging field of software transactional memory promises standard abstractions for writing efficient non-blocking code.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Much research has also been done in providing basic data structures such as stacks, queues, sets, and hash tables.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] These allow programs to easily exchange data between threads asynchronously.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Additionally, some non-blocking data structures are weak enough to be implemented without special atomic primitives.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Several libraries internally use lock-free techniques, but it is difficult to write lock-free code that is correct.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Non-blocking algorithms generally involve a series of read, read-modify-write, and write instructions in a carefully designed order.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Optimizing compilers can aggressively re-arrange operations.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Even when they don't, many modern CPUs often re-arrange such operations (they have a "weak consistency model"), unless a memory barrier is used to tell the CPU not to reorder.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] C++11 programmers can use `std::atomic` in `<atomic>`, and C11 programmers can use `<stdatomic.h>`, both of which supply types and functions that tell the compiler not to re-arrange such instructions, and to insert the appropriate memory barriers.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Wait-freedom is the strongest non-blocking guarantee of progress, combining guaranteed system-wide throughput with starvation-freedom.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is wait-free if every operation has a bound on the number of steps the algorithm will take before the operation completes.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] This property is critical for real-time systems and is always nice to have as long as the performance cost is not too high.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] It was shown in the 1980s that all algorithms can be implemented wait-free, and many transformations from serial code, called *universal constructions*, have been demonstrated.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] However, the resulting performance does not in general match even naïve blocking designs.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Several papers have since improved the performance of universal constructions, but still, their performance is far below blocking designs.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Several papers have investigated the difficulty of creating wait-free algorithms.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] For example, it has been shown that the widely available atomic *conditional* primitives, CAS and LL/SC, cannot provide starvation-free implementations of many common data structures without memory costs growing linearly in the number of threads.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] However, these lower bounds do not present a real barrier in practice, as spending a cache line or exclusive reservation granule (up to 2 KB on ARM) of store per thread in the shared memory is not considered too costly for practical systems.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Typically, the amount of store logically required is a word, but physically CAS operations on the same cache line will collide, and LL/SC operations in the same exclusive reservation granule will collide, so the amount of store physically required is greater.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Wait-free algorithms were rare until 2011, both in research and in practice.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] However, in 2011 Kogan and Petrank presented a wait-free queue building on the CAS primitive, generally available on common hardware.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Their construction expanded the lock-free queue of Michael and Scott, which is an efficient queue often used in practice.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] A follow-up paper by Kogan and Petrank provided a method for making wait-free algorithms fast and used this method to make the wait-free queue practically as fast as its lock-free counterpart.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] A subsequent paper by Timnat and Petrank provided an automatic mechanism for generating wait-free data structures from lock-free ones.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Thus, wait-free implementations are now available for many data-structures.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Under reasonable assumptions, Alistarh, Censor-Hillel, and Shavit showed that lock-free algorithms are practically wait-free.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Thus, in the absence of hard deadlines, wait-free algorithms may not be worth the additional complexity that they introduce.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Lock-freedom allows individual threads to starve but guarantees system-wide throughput.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is lock-free if, when the program threads are run for a sufficiently long time, at least one of the threads makes progress (for some sensible definition of progress).
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] In particular, if one thread is suspended, then a lock-free algorithm guarantees that the remaining threads can still make progress.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Hence, if two threads can contend for the same mutex lock or spinlock, then the algorithm is *not* lock-free.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is lock-free if infinitely often operation by some processors will succeed in a finite number of steps.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] For instance, if *N* processors are trying to execute an operation, some of the *N* processes will succeed in finishing the operation in a finite number of steps and others might fail and retry on failure.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] The difference between wait-free and lock-free is that wait-free operation by each process is guaranteed to succeed in a finite number of steps, regardless of the other processors.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] In general, a lock-free algorithm can run in four phases: completing one's own operation, assisting an obstructing operation, aborting an obstructing operation, and waiting.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Completing one's own operation is complicated by the possibility of concurrent assistance and abortion, but is invariably the fastest path to completion.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] The decision about when to assist, abort or wait when an obstruction is met is the responsibility of a *contention manager*.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] This may be very simple (assist higher priority operations, abort lower priority ones), or may be more optimized to achieve better throughput, or lower the latency of prioritized operations.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Correct concurrent assistance is typically the most complex part of a lock-free algorithm, and often very costly to execute: not only does the assisting thread slow down, but thanks to the mechanics of shared memory, the thread being assisted will be slowed, too, if it is still running.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Obstruction-freedom is the weakest natural non-blocking progress guarantee.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is obstruction-free if at any point, a single thread executed in isolation (i.e., with all obstructing threads suspended) for a bounded number of steps will complete its operation.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] All lock-free algorithms are obstruction-free.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Obstruction-freedom demands only that any partially completed operation can be aborted and the changes made rolled back.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Dropping concurrent assistance can often result in much simpler algorithms that are easier to validate.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Preventing the system from continually live-locking is the task of a contention manager.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Some obstruction-free algorithms use a pair of "consistency markers" in the data structure.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Processes reading the data structure first read one consistency marker, then read the relevant data into an internal buffer, then read the other marker, and then compare the markers.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] The data is consistent if the two markers are identical.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] Markers may be non-identical when the read is interrupted by another process updating the data structure.
[src:tokio-async-rust/non-blocking-algorithm] In such a case, the process discards the data in the internal buffer and tries again.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:tokio-async-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
